<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871118-0046 </DOCNO><HL> Two Former OfficersOf Now-Defunct FirmAre Accused of Fraud</HL><DD> 11/18/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS) </IN><DATELINE> LOS ANGELES  </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal grand jury indicted the former president and the former secretary-treasurer of a now-defunct Santa Monica, Calif.-based video game company on charges of fraud and conspiracy for allegedly filing false financial information with the Securities and Exchange Commission.    George William Atkinson, 49 years old, former president of Video Station Inc., and his brother, Edward Joseph Atkinson, former secretary-treasurer, allegedly omitted $300,000 in accounts payable from the company's 1982 financial statements &quot;in order to falsely show the company earned a profit during 1982 when in fact they suffered a loss,&quot; according to a summary of the indictment. Video Station last reported earnings in 1984.    Robert Alden MacNeil Jr., 27, a former employee of the company, was indicted for allegedly lying to the SEC.    None of the three men could be reached for comment.    If convicted, Edward Atkinson faces as many as 45 years in prison and a fine of as much as $330,000, George Atkinson faces as many as 20 years in prison and a fine of as much as $280,000, and Mr. MacNeil faces as many as five years in prison and a fine of as much as $250,000. </TEXT></DOC>